From 3333333333333333333333333333333333333333 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ASRock Rack <noreply@asrock.com>
Date: Thu, 23 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] dimm: match memoryLocationTable on the full bank+device
 locator

Dimm::dimmDeviceLocator() looks the memoryLocationTable.json entry up by the
SMBIOS Type 17 Device Locator string alone.  That assumes the Device Locator is
unique across the board, which is not true on every BIOS: the ASRock Rack
X570D4I-2T numbers its four SO-DIMM slots per bank, emitting

    Bank Locator     Device Locator
    P0 CHANNEL A     DIMM 0
    P0 CHANNEL A     DIMM 1
    P0 CHANNEL B     DIMM 0
    P0 CHANNEL B     DIMM 1

so all four slots collapse onto two lookup keys and the table cannot express a
distinct Channel for the second bank.

Look the entry up by the same fully-qualified "<bank> <device>" string that is
already published as MemoryDeviceLocator/LocationCode, and fall back to the bare
Device Locator when that misses, so tables written against the old behaviour
keep working unchanged.

Also log the fully-qualified locator on a miss -- "Failed find the corresponding
table for dimm DIMM 0" is ambiguous on exactly the boards this fixes.

Upstream-Status: Pending
--- a/src/dimm.cpp
+++ b/src/dimm.cpp
@@ -226,7 +226,18 @@
 
     if (!data.empty())
     {
-        auto it = data.find(deviceLocator);
+        // Prefer the fully-qualified "<bank> <device>" locator. A table keyed
+        // on the Device Locator alone cannot describe boards whose BIOS
+        // repeats the same Device Locator string in every bank -- the ASRock
+        // X570D4I-2T reports "DIMM 0"/"DIMM 1" under both "P0 CHANNEL A" and
+        // "P0 CHANNEL B", so four slots collapse onto two keys. Fall back to
+        // the bare Device Locator so existing tables keep working.
+        auto it = data.find(result);
+
+        if (it == data.end())
+        {
+            it = data.find(deviceLocator);
+        }
 
         if (it != data.end())
         {
@@ -248,7 +259,7 @@
             slot(0);
             channel(0);
             lg2::error("Failed find the corresponding table for dimm {DIMM}",
-                       "DIMM", deviceLocator.c_str());
+                       "DIMM", result.c_str());
         }
     }
     else
